ss regardless of whether the authentication actually succeeded. This means the precondition never confirmed that ops-user was working—it just tried and moved on. So both users are failing authentication because the secrets containing their credentials were created but never mounted into the pods where Elasticsearch can access them.\n\nThe solution is to combine both user secrets into a single aggregate secret and mount it at the file realm path so Elasticsearch can read the users and roles files. Since I can't modify the StatefulSet without triggering a rolling restart that could destabilize the cluster, I need to find a minimal patching approach that gets the credentials mounted without disrupting the running nodes. So the real issue is that the two secrets were never mounted to the pods in the first place. The solution is to merge the report-user credentials from the separate secret into the aggregate secret, then mount that aggregate secret to the StatefulSets. I could either patch the StatefulSets to trigger a rolling restart, or exec directly into pods to write the files without restarting, though the latter isn't persistent. Given the health constraint, I should probably go with the graceful StatefulSet approach.\n\nActually, there's a better path here—Elasticsearch's file realm automatically watches for changes to the users file and reloads it without needing a restart. So I can decode and merge the user data from both secrets, exec into each pod to write the merged files directly, and then update the aggregate secret with the merged content for persistence when new pods spin up.\n\nFor a permanent solution, I'll need to patch the StatefulSets to mount the merged secret at the correct paths using subPath. A rolling restart with proper readiness probes should be safe given the cluster has 5 nodes with redundancy, though I want to minimize disruption if possible.\n\nThe key insight is that Elasticsearch already reads from `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/users`